 Abstract 
 Chile is one of the few countries that has encouraged the use of markets in water useful thing/valuable supply management. In order to test the hit/effect of 
 water markets and transactions costs in Chile, four river valleys, the Maipo, Elqui, Limari, and the Azapa were selected as case studies. 
 Transactions from the Elqui and Limari valleys, during the years 1986 to 1993, were carefully studied to decide/figure out the gains-from-trade from 
 market moves (from one place to another). 
 In the money-based and (money-related) analysis of water markets, crop budgets were used to guess the value of water in farming-based 
 production. The value of water-use rights to city-based  water-supply companies was guessed using the avoided cost of an different 
 investment in a water-storage holding tank. The analysis (showed/shown or proved) that the market move (from one place to another) of water-use rights does produce big 
 money-based gains-from-trade in both the Elqui and Limari Valleys. These money-based gains produce rents for both buyers and sellers. But 
 buyers, especially farmers growing money-making crops who buy water-use rights and people buying water-use rights for drinkable water 
 supply, receive higher rents then sellers. Large table-grape producers in the Limari Valley and people buying water for human 
 consumption in the Elqui Valley received the highest rents. In the Elqui Valley net gains-from-trade per share were within the range of 
 recent move (from one place to another) prices of US$1000. In the Limari Valley, gains-from-trade per share are 3.4 times the recent prices of US$3000 for a share of 
 water from the Cogoti Holding tank. 
 Where trading was active, especially in the Limari Valley, transactions costs have not presented an noticeable (blocking thing) to trading. 
 Anyway, in the large narrow waterway systems with fixed flow dividers in the Elqui and Maipo Valley there have been very few transactions. 
 Different factors add/give to the lack of trading, but the (not being there; not being present) of trading in these large narrow waterway systems highlights the costs of changing 
 fixed (set of machines), especially for trades between farmers. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 With the growing concern about the increased 
 (not enough of something) and inefficient portion and use of water 
 useful things/valuable supplies, much attention has been focused on the 
 use of markets in water portion. A market based 
 portion could secure water supplies for high-value 
 uses in city-based  and areas away from cities without the need to 
 develop expensive, new sources of supply that may be 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) damaging. Also by securing com- 
 
 ' Corresponding author. 
 
 pensation for water moved (from one place to another) from low valued uses, 
 water markets provide an (reward or reason for doing something) for (producing more with less waste) 
 water use in farming-based, industrial, and city-based 
 uses. What's more, if markets work properly, price 
 signals can provide the information needed for (producing a lot with very little waste) water portion more effectively than models 
 developed by a central water supplies management 
 (service business/government unit/power/functioning) (Rosegrant and Binswanger, 1994). 
 The effectiveness of water markets is held back 
 by the ability of buyers and sellers to measure and 
 transport water, to (make something permitted by law) and enforce transactions, 
 and to account for water quality. So, the effect of 
 transactions costs and the (set of machines) and institu- 
 
