 tions that reduce these transactions costs are critical 
 to the effectiveness of water markets. Also, the 
 (free to move around/without rules or restrictions) movement of water via private exchanges can produce negative external effects on 
 third party users. There is also the fear that the free 
 exchange of water may disadvantage poor people. 
 Because of these concerns there is continued doubt 
 among water useful thing/valuable supply managers, policy makers, and 
 analysts of the type and extent of benefits that happen 
 with (the creation of/the beginning of the existence of) move (from one place to another)able water-use 
 rights. There is continued doubt that (the creation of/the beginning of the existence of) move (from one place to another)able water-use rights is (good) enough for 
 the creation of an active market that will fairly 
 (give out things in a different way) water. And there is concern that if trading 
 does happen that the benefits of these trades will be 
 captured by only a small group of landowners and 
 (people or businesss who give money to help start businesses). 
 As a result, it is important to carefully study Chile's 
 experience with move (from one place to another)able water-use rights since 
 Chile is one of the few countries that has encouraged 
 the use of water markets. Market portion in Chile 
 is possible, in part, because a system of move (from one place to another)able 
 water-use rights was reestablished in 1981. These 
 rights are independent of land use and land ownership, this way trade of water rights is fairly (having no limits, rules, or barriers). 
 The (putting something into law) of these water-use rights (happened at the same time 
 with a series of changes in the Chilean (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 including (turned over from the government to private companies) land rights and liberalized trade. 
 This paper presents a description and an analysis 
 of water portion and water markets in Chile, with 
 a focus on areas of (compared to other things) frequent trades. 
 The first part of the paper provides a brief introduction. This is followed by an analysis of money-based 
 and (money-related) gains-from-trade as well as a description of the water markets. The paper then ends/decides 
 with some (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) about the water markets in Chile and the institutions that help trading. 
 1.1. Water markets, transactions costs, and institutions 
 
 As an introduction to a discussion of water markets it is useful to tell the difference between the exchange 
 of water and the exchange of water-use rights. This 
 is appropriate because the honor/difference highlights the 
 importance of the institutional arrangements for water useful thing/valuable supply portion. The former - sometimes 
 
 referred to as a 'spot market' - happens when the 
 owner of a legal or (related to giving rules and instructions) right to a certain 
 volume or flow of water sells a part of/amount of that water, 
 sometimes outside of punishment, to a neighbor in 
 a simple transaction. These exchanges are for a limited 
 period of time - sometimes for only a few hours of 
 crop-watering/rinsing with water. Although the unit of sales may not be 
 metered volumetrically, both buyer and seller have 
 good information on the amount/quantity involved. A more 
 permanent transaction involves the exchange of the 
 water-use right itself. This generally needs/demands legal 
 sanction to maintain the security of the right after the 
 move (from one place to another). These moves (from one place to another) are usually permanent, but 
 can be for a limited, but extended period of time - at 
 least one crop-watering/rinsing with water season. And the load of uncertain supply will fall on the purchaser of the right. 
 Where water is very hard to find and legally defined move (from one place to another)able water-use rights exist, market trades can be 
 expected when the difference in the value of water 
 between two uses is greater than the costs of moving (from one place to another) the water. Without transactions costs 
 money-based (rewards or reasons for doing something) would cause water users to 
 trade water-use rights until the not important value of 
 these rights was equal across all users. Of course; 
 transactions costs do limit the movement of water 
 and the move (from one place to another) of water-use rights. Transactions 
 costs for water market moves (from one place to another) include: (i) the cost 
 of the physical (set of machines) needed to measure and 
 transport water, including the (change from a liquid to a gas) and filtration losses during transportation; (ii) the cost of searching and finding willing buyers and sellers, and nego&#126; 
 tiating a contract; and (iii) the cost of validating legal 
 ownership of the water-use right, (making something permitted by law) the contract, enforcing contract (legal rules), and owning 
 the necessary permission from legal/law-based people in charge 
 to move (from one place to another) water. Because these transactions costs 
 can be large, the number of possible buyers and 
 sellers may be limited - which may result in non&#126; 
 competitive pricing. 
 The market exchange of water and water-use 
 rights is a (compared to other things) rare thing/event, and so the 
 money-based analyses of actual exchanges are rare. A 
 few studies have tested out the effects of market and 
 (related to managing and running a company or organization) moves (from one place to another) in the western USA (Vaux 
 and Howitt, 1984; Carve and reducesey and Houston, 1984; 
 Hamilton et al., 1989; Dinar and Letey, 1991; Rosen 
 and Church assistant, 1993; and Weinberg et al., 1993). Other 
 studies have depended on data from actual trades in 
 
 R.R. Hearne, K.W. Easter/ Farming-based Money flow 15 (1997) 187-199 
 
 order to test the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of water markets. 
 Maass and Anderson (1978) tested the water 
 market in Alicante, Spain, and found that the market 
 system produced greater net increases in (related to a large area) 
 income than the rotation systems. Chang and Griffin 
 (1992) guessed the gains-from-trade for moves (from one place to another) 
 from farming to city-based water supply. Finally, 
 Colby (1990) guessed the transactions costs needed/demanded to get approval of water moves (from one place to another) and the 
 lawsuits costs of third party challenges and suggests 
 that this is not overly heavy. 
 
 1.2. Water portion institutions in Chile 
 Chile has a tradition of private development of 
 water supplies and private rights to shares of river 
 and narrow waterway flows that dates to the colonial time. This 
 tradition was reestablished in the National Water 
 Code of 1981 (D.F.L. Number 1122) which allows 
 private move (from one place to another)able property rights for water use. 
 The 1981 water law says that water is a national 
 useful thing/valuable supply for public use but that permanent and move (from one place to another)able rights to use water can be granted to 
 people obeying the law. Water-use 
 rights can be granted by the government upon written request, can be (bought something for money) from an individual owner, or 
 can be kept/held based on traditional use. Now, 
 there is no condition that water-use rights must be 
 used in order to be kept/held. 
 The law says that rights are to be specified 
 by volume of flow per unit of time. But in most river 
 valleys rights are defined as a share of stream flow, 
 because the high (quality of changing over time or at different places) of natural river flows 
 prohibits volumetric (detailed description of exactly what is required). Since sick use rights are granted for the full use of all the 
 water said in the right, no downstream user has 
 any right to return flows created from upstream 
 users. Downstream rights holders are not protected 
 by law from any change in upstream water use that 
 reduces (a lot) return flows. There is also no 
 restriction on the move (from one place to another) of upstream water to another (bowl/area drained by a river). 
 The Direcci6n General de Aguas is responsible 
 for water supplies planning and the development 
 and abuse of water supplies. It collects data 
 on water supplies, maintains cadastres of water use, 
 and has limited authority to get involved and help in conflicts 
 between water users. The Direcci6n General de 
 
 189 
 
 Aguas also grants, upon petition, water-use rights for 
 surface and ground water that is not already claimed. 
 These grants are a matter of public record. During 
 times of drought the Direcci6n General de Aguas can 
 (take and hold) water, with payment to holders of 
 water-use rights. 
 Although the Direcci6n General de Aguas does 
 have broad authority in water supplies management, 
 much of the actual control over river flows is exercised by the local river watching people in charge, the 
 (rulers)s de lookoutancia (JDV). These JDV manage and 
 maintain storage holding tanks, and are responsible for 
 reducing the flow of water to narrow waterways during times of 
 water (not enough of something). The JDV are controlled by the river's 
 water-use rights holders on a particular section of a 
 river. This way in some river (bowls/areas drained by a river), irrigators, mining 
 companies, and water supply companies are part of 
 the same JDV. Now, the court system is the 
 final judge of water-use conflicts. 
 (in the past), the development of crop-watering/rinsing with water in Chile 
 has been ruled by the (people and businesses that are not part of the government). All privately developed crop-watering/rinsing with water systems and many of 
 those developed by the state are owned and controlled by independent water user associations 
 (WUAs). These WUAs are owned and operated by 
 their members, and charge fees based on the their 
 capital and operating costs. The WUAs maintain the 
 narrow waterway systems, keep records of rights holders, give out water to individual rights holders according to 
 their recorded shares, and enforce water rights. The 
 1981 Water Code specifies rules for the (creation and construction/ group of objects), 
 control, and responsibilities of these WUAs. 
 
 2. Calculation of gains-from-trade and money-based 
 rents 
 In order to test the hit/effect of water markets and 
 transactions costs in Chile, four river valleys, the 
 upper Maipo in Chile's central valley, and the Elqui 
 and Limarf valleys in north-central Chile, and the 
 Azapa Valley in the far north of Chile were selected 
 as case studies (Hearne, 1995; Hearne and Easter, 
 1995). These valleys were identified based on prior 
 information that suggested that there was - or should 
 be - active trading in the area. Attempts were made 
 to identify all transactions of water-use rights in 
 these areas for the years 1986-1993. These years 
 
 190 
 
 R.R. Hearne, K.W. Easter j Farming-based Money flow 15 (1997) 187-199 
 
 were chosen because of reports of more active water 
 trading over the last few years, because they include both 
 wet and dry years, and because farmers were expected to provide more correct information on recent transactions. Water transactions in conjunction 
 with land transactions were generally not thought about/believed, 
 because they usually do not represent a change in 
 water-use patterns. 
 A survey test/list of questions was developed to ask for/encourage 
 information from farmers who have participated in 
 water market transactions. This information included: (i) individual (features/ qualities/ traits) of buyers and 
 sellers; (ii) water transactions, including price, amount, and transactions costs; and (iii) farmer's crop 
 yields. In order to maintain the confidence of the 
 person who responded in the survey procedure questions on 
 incomes and tax rates were avoided. 1 
 People making transactions were identified 
 from records of WUAs, from local real estate registries, and from other transacting parties. 
 Farm experts from the Universidad Cat6lica of Santiago were recruited as enumerators. Attempts were 
 made to contact all people who had made transactions in the areas selected for analysis. Managers 
 of city-based  water-supply companies and industrial users 
 of water were also interviewed. 
 2.1. Crop budget analysis in valuing water rights 
 
 The net returns, calculated using farm budget 
 analyses, is an upper bound to farmer's desire 
 to pay for water in crop-watering/rinsing with water. This is not a not important 
 analysis, but an guess of the average value of 
 water. The net returns to a farmer are the maximum 
 that a farmer could pay for water and land, and still 
 break even. In this study, farm budgets are used for 
 both an money-based and (money-related) analysis of water 
 markets. Net returns are divided between land and 
 water according to relative market values (asked for/encouraged 
 
