 In Chile farming-based taxes are fairly complex. A 
 simple option for farmers is to pay a land tax of 10% 
 of the tested value. Because land tests are 
 generally not up to date, the stated tested value is 
 probably much less than the market value reported in 
 the survey, and for this reason reported market values are discounted by 50%. Land taxes payments 
 were deducted from net money/money income in the (money-related) 
 analysis of rents to buyers and sellers. These payments were not deducted from net money/money income in the 
 money-based analysis because they are move (from one place to another) payments and do not reflect a net loss to (community of people/all good people in the world). 
 2.2. Value of water for drinkable water supply in the 
 Elqui Valley 
 The value of water-use rights in the Elqui River 
 for drinkable water supply can be figured out by/decided by the 
 purchaser's ability to go before the need to invest in 
 more expensive other choices to get water supplies. 
 Since the demand for water in this service area will 
 continue to rise, the least cost other choice for meeting 
 this demand - without effective water 
 markets - is the appropriate way(s) of doing things for testing the value of water. Ground water in this area is 
 very deep, and of poor quality, and would not be a 
 (producing a lot for a given amount of money) other choice, except for emergency supplies in summer months. 
 The first (or most important) other choice for drinkable water supply 
 would be to construct a holding tank in the Elqui Valley. 
 In fact, ESSCO, the city-based water-supply company which services the valley's crowded coastal 
 area, (chose to not do something) of a proposed group effort with the 
 Ministry of Public Work's Direcci6n de Riego to 
 construct the Puclaro Dam on the Rfo Elqui. At a 
 cost of US$23 500 000, ESSCO was offered (good) enough ability (to hold or do something) in the proposed holding tank to meet its 
 needs for secure water supplies well into the next 
 century. 3 ESSCO's refusal of this offer (happened at the same time 
 with its current program to buy water-use rights 
 on the Elqui River. 
