 res( w) =seller s's transactions costs. To the buyer, 
 the net rent is the difference between the value of 
 water to the buyer and the sum of the buyer's 
 purchase price and transactions cost, as shown in Eq. 
 (4): 
 NR&#126;( w) 
 
 = 
 
 V/( w)- [P,w(b,slw 
 
 + TCb( w)]_). 
 
 ( 4) 
 
 As reported, the sum of rents to buyers and sellers 
 does not equal the calculated gains-from-trade. This 
 is because money-based gains differ from (money-related) rents. 
 Also, for some transactions both buyer and seller 
 were not interviewed, and (money-related) rents are calculated and reported only for interviewed parties. 
 
 3. Results 
 Only the transactions from the Elqui and Limarf 
 valleys were carefully studied to decide/figure out the gains-fromtrade from market moves (from one place to another). In the upper Maipo 
 valley transactions were rare - except for water-use 
 rights gave up to city-based water companies from 
 developers of crowded land - and were not included in the analysis. (in almost the same way), in the Azapa valley 
 only a few transactions were identified and gainsfrom-trade were not calculated. In the Elqui valley 
 transactions were rare, but there is significant 
 intersectoral move (from one place to another) as well as a slow move (from one place to another) of 
 water-use rights within farming. In the Limarf 
 Valley, with its well-developed system of crop-watering/rinsing with water 
 (set of machines) and well-organized WUAs, transactions are fairly frequent. 
 3 .1. The Elqui Valley 
 The Elqui Valley in Chile's Area IV supplies 
 water for 18 700 ha of farmland as well as drinkable 
 water for a medium-sized city (250 000 residents) 
 with a very large summer population. A small tourist 
