 employed by their owners at the time of sale is a 
 large factor in these high money-based rents. 
 3.2. The Limarf Valley 
 
 South of the Elqui Valley in Area IV is the 
 productive Limarf Valley, which contains the Rfo 
 Limarf and its streams the Cogotf, Grande, Guatalame, Hurtado, and Rapel. This valley has 50000 ha 
 of watered farmland producing table grapes, pisco 
 grapes, (plant-related) products, basic grains, and pas- 
 
 195 
 
 ture. A central feature of this valley is the presence 
 of a large interconnected system of three interseasonal storage holding tanks: Paloma (750 million m 3 ), 
 Cogotf (150 million m 3 ), and Recoleta (100 million 
 m 3 ). This storage along with gated narrow waterways and wellorganized WUAs allows for volumetric (detailed description of exactly what is required) 
 of water-use rights. This is a dry area with mean 
 once-a-year (rain, snow, etc.) of 140 mm. There is one small 
 city, Ovalle, with a population of 80000 that draws 
 water from the Rfo Limarf. 
 In the Limarf Valley, a population of all water 
 transactions was not developed. Instead, data collection was (focused mental and physical effort) on areas with frequent transactions and people with many transactions. Attempts were made to balance interviews in these 
 areas with other areas of less market activity. In the 
 areas of the Rfo Hurtado and Rfo Grande which 
 irrigate a total of 5400 ha above the Recoleta and 
 Paloma Dams (match up each pair of items in order), only a handful of transactions were identified. All other identified transactions 
 were in areas below the holding tanks. Each WUA 
 assigns a different amount of water to each share. 7 
 Because of this all water-use rights were converted 
 to an average volumetric (religious group/category of paper money), based on 
 survey results. 
 The low transactions costs and frequent trades in 
 the valley can be attributed to both modem (set of machines) and well-developed WUAs. Because of 
 holding tank storage and gated narrow waterways, water is delivered 
 to farmers on demand and a water move (from one place to another) is almost 
 costless. So, the frequency of move (from one place to another) is high and 
 the market for water-use rights is active. People 
 easily separate water from land and farmers make 
 not important water-use decisions. 
