 3.3. The Maipo Valley 
 
 The first section of the Maipo River supplies 
 water to 4.5 million people in the Santiago area as 
 well as watering over 30 000 ha. The river is divided 
 into 8133 shares, each representing 8ljs, 85% of the 
 time. In this first section of the river, there have been 
 very few transactions of water-use rights in the past 
 eight years. The City-based (keeping things clean and disease-free) Works 
 Company (EMOS) has contracted a team of lawyers 
 to buy rights but has (bought something for money) only 33 shares 
 of the upper Maipo in the last eight years, with 
 prices averaging US$1 0 000 per share. The only 
 industrial concern to buy water rights was a 
 paper mill which made two (instances of buying things for money) totalling 4.5 
 shares. There are also very few permanent trades 
 between farmers. In the large narrow waterway systems of five 
 WUAs, distributing 65% of the crop-watering/rinsing with water water in 
 this section of the river, there were only a handful of 
 trades between farmers. All of the narrow waterways serving 
 these five WUAs have fixed flow dividers controlling 
 the distribution of water. 
 3.4. The Azapa Valley 
 
 The Azapa Valley, which is located in the downstream section of the San Jose river (bowl/area drained by a river)  in Chile's 
 far north Area I, supports 3280 areas of land of watered 
 farmland and the city of Arica (population 160000). 
 This valley, bordering the very dry Atacama 
 Desert, is very dry and rainfall in the lower reaches 
 is very small. The Water Supply and (keeping things clean and disease-free) Company of Tarapaca (ESSAT), which supplies water to 
 Arica, has been able to use rental agreements to meet 
 the (for only a short time) (very simple/rough and rude) water needs of the city of Arica. 
 ESSAT rents wells from owners of ground-water 
 rights. Different government (services businesses/government units), responding to a 
 presidential order to give the Arica water supply a 
 priority in government action, have helped in the 
 process of renting wells. In the (back-and-forth conversations to agree on something) process, 
 ESSAT was able to call for/use both the government's 
 appeal to farmers to release water for Arica and the 
 possibility that the state could (take and hold) water during 
 periods of extreme water shortage. ESSA T has not 
 needed to buy water from users of a surface 
 narrow waterway in the Azapa valley, because the ground-water 
 
 197 
 
 supplies were made available. This way the recent additions to the Arica water supply is much more a result 
 of government action than of market activity. 
 In these arrangements ESSAT digs or heals 
 a well, installs and operates a pump, delivers free of 
 charge a few hours of water per week to the rights 
 owner, and pays a rental fee for the use of the well. 
 ESSAT will then pump water from the well continuously, whereas an irrigator only uses the water a few 
 hours per week. This rental arrangement is quite 
 moneymaking to the individual irrigator, who does not 
 soak up the negative externality of a used up/reduced underground water, 
 at least in the short run. Since these rental contracts 
 can be ended/fired by either party, it is probable that 
 a few will be ended/fired after ESSAT receives water 
 from the wells that are now being healed 
 in the Andean highlands. 
 
 4. (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) and ends/end results 
 Chile's history of privately developed crop-watering/rinsing with water, 
 and its traditional portion of river water by shares, 
 has created a good climate for the establishment 
 of move (from one place to another)able water-use rights. These rights have 
 secured water supply to irrigators and so gave/given 
 an enabling (surrounding conditions) for investment in permanent fruit crops and improved crop-watering/rinsing with water technology. 
 The overall growth in the value of Chile's farming-based output during the last ten years can be attributed 
 to different changes in both input and output markets. 
 The effects of the 1981 Water Code on the farming-based part/area cannot be fully separated from the effects 
 of liberalized trade and secured land rights. But the 
 farming-based part/area that is highly dependent on crop-watering/rinsing with water has expanded without new investments in crop-watering/rinsing with water (set of machines). 
 This research has (showed/shown or proved) that the market 
 move (from one place to another) of water-use rights does produce big 
 money-based gains-from-trade in both the Elqui and 
 Limarf Valleys in north-central Chile. These money-based gains happen in intersectoral trades and in 
 trades between farmers, and they produce rents for 
 both buyers and sellers. Yet buyers, especially large 
 table-grape producers in the Limarf Valley and people buying water-use rights for drinkable water 
 supply in the Elqui Valley, receive higher rents then 
 sellers. In the Elqui Valley total and net gains-from- 
 
 198 
 
 R.R. Hearne, K.W. Easter/ Farming-based Money flow 15 (1997) 187-199 
 
 trade per share were within the range of recent 
 move (from one place to another) prices of US$1 000 per share. In the Limarf 
 Valley, gains-from-trade from shares of water-use 
 rights are 3.4 times the recent transaction prices of 
 US$3000 for a share of water from the Cogotf 
 Holding tank (one share delivers 4250 m 3 in an average 
 year). 
 One of the most interesting result of this analysis 
 is the small money-based gains from intersectoral trade in the Elqui Valley. Although the value 
 of water in city-based water supply is high, the value 
 of water to money-making farmers is also high. When 
 water is moved (from one place to another) from these money-making farmers, the 
 money-based gains from this (giving out things in a different way) are small. 
 Even if water is not used by its owner, it is generally 
 used by other farmers. If these farmers are money-making, 
 then the money-based gains of the (giving out things in a different way) are small, 
 even though the (money-related) gain to the seller is large. 
 These four case studies (show or prove) the (many different kinds of people or things) 
 of water portion and water management in northern and central Chile. In three of the four areas 
 studied, especially where large narrow waterway systems use 
 fixed flow dividers, market transactions were rare. Even though these valleys were chosen 
 for analysis because of expectations that they had 
 (compared to other things) active local water markets, only the Limarf 
 Valley had active trading. In this valley, transactions 
 costs are low and trade between farmers is helped 
 by the presence of holding tank storage, gated narrow waterways 
 with flow meters, and well-organized WUAs. In the 
 Elqui Valley, the presence of many short narrow waterways 
 flowing from the river also reduces the costs of 
 physically changing the flow of water. 
 In large narrow waterway systems with fixed flow dividers, 
 the cost of changing stream flows might be way too high especially for trades among farmers, as suggested by the lack of trading in the Narrow waterway Bellavista system in the Elqui Valley and the large narrow waterway 
 systems in the upper Maipo Valley. Sales of not important 
 amounts of extra water are far from typical. Many 
 decisions on investment and crop selection have 
 been based on the joint landjwater portion that 
 resulted from the final stages of land reform. 12 
 12 In the final stages of land reform, land stolen/stole before 
 1974 was divided into family farms equal in value to 8 
 watered ha. Water rights usually/(in the past) assigned to the land were 
 distributed to the landowners. 
 
 What's more, WUAs play an important role in 
 helping the market (giving out things in a different way) of water, especially in the Limarf Valley where trading is active 
 and in the Elqui Valley where intersectoral trading 
 happens. Many of these WUAs have been able to 
 change to fit the needs of their members for services that 
 help or stop transactions. 
 The proposed Puclaro Dam project, on the Elqui 
 River upstream of La Serena, is an example of how 
 the presence of a market other choice to water portion may reduce politica<p><strong>NOTE: This document is incomplete. It was shortened to the maximum document length of 50,000 characters.</strong></p><div style="clear:both">&nbsp;</div>
